## Running tests

```bash
make test       # fast, no coverage
make test-cov   # with branch coverage report
```

## Layout

```
tests/
  conftest.py       # shared fixtures
  unit/             # pure logic, no I/O
  integration/      # real I/O (db, filesystem, network)
```

Keep unit tests fast and free of I/O. Integration tests may use real databases, real files, or real HTTP — never mocks of those boundaries.

## Dependency-direction tests

The layered architecture must be enforced by tests, not just convention. Write AST-based import checks for every boundary that matters in this project.

```python
# tests/test_imports.py
import ast
from pathlib import Path


def imports_of(path: Path) -> set[str]:
    tree = ast.parse(path.read_text())
    result: set[str] = set()
    for node in ast.walk(tree):
        match node:
            case ast.Import():
                result.update(alias.name for alias in node.names)
            case ast.ImportFrom() if node.module:
                result.add(node.module)
    return result


def all_imports_in(directory: Path) -> set[str]:
    result: set[str] = set()
    for path in directory.rglob("*.py"):
        result |= imports_of(path)
    return result


# Example: database adapter must not import from cli or api layers.
# Add similar assertions for every architectural boundary in this project.
def test_db_does_not_import_cli() -> None:
    src = Path("{{ src }}/{{ pkg }}")
    db_imports = all_imports_in(src / "db")
    forbidden = {
        m for m in db_imports
        if m.startswith("{{ pkg }}.cli") or m.startswith("{{ pkg }}.api")
    }
    assert not forbidden, f"db layer imports upper layers: {forbidden}"
```

Add one test function per boundary. Name them `test_<layer>_does_not_import_<upper_layer>`.

## Fixtures

- Define fixtures in `conftest.py` at the appropriate scope (root for shared, subdirectory for local).
- Prefer function scope. Use session scope only for expensive resources that are genuinely read-only (e.g., a pre-built schema).

## Coverage

Target: branch coverage over the `{{ src }}/{{ pkg }}` package. Coverage config is in `pyproject.toml`. View the HTML report in `htmlcov/` after `make test-cov`.

Missing coverage on a branch is not always a bug — exclude deliberately unreachable branches with `# pragma: no cover`.
